The "'''Second Thirty Years' War'''" is a [[periodization]] scheme sometimes used by historians to encompass the wars in Europe from 1914 to 1945.{{efn|name=term}}

Just as the [[Thirty Years' War]] of 1618 to 1648 was not a single war but a series of conflicts in varied times and locations, later organized and named by historians into a single period, the Second Thirty Years' War has been seen as a "[[European Civil War]]", fought over the problem of Germany and exacerbated by new ideologies such as [[communism]], [[fascism]], and [[Nazism]].<ref name="HKU 2013">
